;;; RULES.slat — graph-of-world/ subcollection rules
;;; Sibling to graph-of-store/, graph-of-brand/, graph-of-life/,
;;; graph-of-person/, graph-of-science/ inside objects/.

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura") :note "Rules apply to both dialects.")

(rules
  :collection      "graph-of-world"
  :version         "1.0.0"
  :created         "2026-07-16"
  :owner           "Alfred"
  :parent-rules    "/Users/alfred/code/curator/objects/RULES.slat"

  :purpose
  "Structured knowledge about the PHYSICAL, BIOLOGICAL, GEOGRAPHICAL and
   NATURAL things Sakura reasons over. Body parts, animals, plants,
   weather, phenomena, places, seasons, times of day, vehicles, and raw
   materials. This is the graph Sakura consults when a listing says
   'kelp forest', 'monsoon-season', 'oak beam', or 'canyon light'. It is
   also the graph a kid browses when they want to know what a pangolin
   is. It is NOT the commerce graph (store-objects) and NOT the identity
   graph (brand-objects) — it is the WORLD."

  :shape
  "FACETED CLASSIFICATION per Ranganathan + type-theory descent. Each
   node is ONE record with typed facets. Facets are declared in
   FACETS.slat. Values enumerate what actually appears in the corpus;
   we do not pre-invent categories. Nodes cluster by CATEGORY (body /
   animal / plant / weather / place / time / vehicle / material) via
   the :category facet — one root graph, not eight."

  :scope-and-coverage
  "Target: ~30-50k nodes covering ~80% of naming volume across the eight
   subcategories, per lane brief:
     - body parts:            ~300
     - animals:               ~10-15k (from GBIF backbone + WordNet)
     - plants:                ~10-20k (from Kew World Checklist + WordNet)
     - weather + phenomena:   ~200-500
     - places (habitat/geo):  ~500-1k
     - times of day + seasons: ~50-100
     - vehicles (general):    ~100-200
     - raw materials:         ~200-500
   Where the aggregate exceeds 50k, prioritize by cultural centrality
   first (things kids see and name), then broadening. Sakura would
   rather know 'oak' well than 500 obscure sedges shallowly."

  :cross-graph-references-not-duplication
  "graph-of-world' :made-of facet points into itself (materials are
   world-nodes). Its :used-for and :material-for facets point into
   store-objects/ or life-objects/. Its :for-species facet points back
   into itself. Its :region-native-to facet resolves to :place-type
   world-nodes. None of these facets duplicate content; resolution
   fails gracefully with :ref-unresolved."

  :synonym-minimum
  "Every node carries MINIMUM 3 synonyms. Includes:
     - alternate common names (fir tree / fir / evergreen fir)
     - regional variants (torch / flashlight, autumn / fall)
     - scientific name where applicable (short form: 'Quercus alba')
     - at least one non-English translation for high-centrality nodes
     - kid-vocabulary forms where they diverge ('puppy' for young dog)
   Aim for 5-15 where the node has cross-cultural naming variance."

  :provenance-mandatory
  "Every node carries :provenance with the source of the record.
   Wikidata QID preferred (CC0). WordNet synset id secondary (WordNet
   license = permissive). GBIF taxon id where applicable (CC-BY 4.0).
   Kew World Checklist for plants (CC-BY 3.0). Manual authoring OK for
   well-known everyday nodes but tagged :authored-by 'graph-of-world-lane'."

  :license-conservative
  "SOURCES USED:
     - Wikidata (CC0)
     - WordNet 3.1 (Princeton license — permissive, attribution)
     - OMW / Open Multilingual WordNet (per-language licenses; we cite
       language-of-origin per translation)
     - GBIF backbone (CC-BY 4.0) for species names + taxonomy
     - Kew World Checklist of Vascular Plants (CC-BY 3.0)
     - ITIS (public domain, US Federal)
     - schema.org vocabulary (CC-BY-SA — vocabulary only, no data)
   SOURCES NOT USED:
     - Any paid proprietary taxonomic database
     - Any dataset without a clear public/permissive license
     - Scraped iNaturalist observations (their photos are per-user
       licensed, and we don't need photos in a flat graph)"

  :no-corporate-names
  "graph-of-world contains NO corporate/brand names. A 'car' node
   exists; specific makers live in brand-objects. A 'yacht' node
   exists; specific yacht builders live in brand-objects. A 'ferry'
   node exists; the Staten Island Ferry does not. Same for plants
   ('rose' yes, 'David Austin roses' no — that's brand-objects)."

  :ancient-name-collision-carveout
  "Certain vendor / product names collide with pre-existing English
   words for natural-world things. When that happens the NATURAL-
   WORLD sense IS preserved; the LLM/vendor sense is never introduced.
   Explicit examples in v1.0:
     - 'gemini'   = the constellation (Latin twins). Not the model.
     - 'mistral'  = the cold north wind from France. Not the model.
     - 'llama'    = the South American camelid. Not the model.
     - 'meta'     = we do NOT introduce this word — it is not a
                    natural-world thing.
   Nothing changes semantically; we simply carry the ancient/natural
   sense that predates the vendor by centuries or millennia."

  :append-only
  "Once landed, this graph grows by APPEND (new nodes, new edges, new
   synonyms). Species reclassifications → new record with :succeeds
   pointing at prior canonical id, prior record kept with :status
   :renamed-to. NO rewrites. Alfred 2026-07-16."

  :never-hallucinate-facts
  "If you don't KNOW the native range of a species, omit the facet.
   If you don't KNOW whether a weather phenomenon has a seasonal tie,
   omit the facet. Missing is honest. Wrong is not. Sakura would
   rather have a nil field than a made-up one."

  :files-in-this-collection
  ((:name "RULES.slat"              :purpose "this file — collection rules")
   (:name "README.slat"             :purpose "orientation for new authors")
   (:name "MANIFEST.slat"           :purpose "book-level metadata Sakura reads")
   (:name "FACETS.slat"             :purpose "the attribute-facet schema — declares all facets, value types, and enumerated value lists")
   (:name "GRAPH-OF-WORLD-1.0.slat" :purpose "main flat file — one (node ...) record per entry, plus (edge ...) intra-graph records")
   (:name "SYNONYMS-INDEX.slat"     :purpose "lookup from any name variant → canonical node id")
   (:name "CROSS-REFS.slat"         :purpose "cross-graph edges — world-node → store-object / life-object / other, with weight + provenance")
   (:name "build.py"                :purpose "seed-loader + SLAT emitter — regenerate the three flat files from seeds/")
   (:name "seeds/"                  :purpose "directory of Python seed files, one per category-family, that supply typed dicts to build.py"))

  :notice
  "This collection incorporates content derived from Wikidata (CC0),
   WordNet 3.1 (Princeton License), GBIF backbone (CC-BY 4.0), Kew
   World Checklist (CC-BY 3.0), and ITIS (public domain). Derivative
   records preserve source ids in :provenance and inherit source
   licensing. Records authored fresh at the graph-of-world-lane are
   dedicated to the public domain under CC0."

  :non-blocking-caveats
  "1. Species-level exhaustiveness is impossible in one lane; we take
      the ~10-15k most-recognized common names, plus family/order
      backbone for taxonomy walks.
   2. Regional-plants coverage is deliberately global-general; kid-
      friendly common flora first, then broaden.
   3. Weather-phenomena naming varies by culture (haboob, monsoon,
      sirocco) — we include named regional phenomena where they carry
      cross-cultural recognition.
   4. Times-of-day and seasons include multi-cultural senses
      (equinox, monsoon, dry-season, cherry-blossom-season)."

  :composition-with-other-graphs
  "graph-of-store references world-nodes via :material-for (a wooden
   spoon's :made-of points at 'wood'), :seasonal-for (a scarf's
   :seasonal-for points at 'winter'), and :for-species (a dog-collar's
   :for-species points at 'dog').

   graph-of-life references world-nodes for setting (a kitchen
   scenario references 'kitchen' place-node; a lonely-morning scenario
   references 'morning' time-node).

   graph-of-event references world-nodes for temporal + geographic
   context (a birthday-party at 'evening' in 'backyard').

   graph-of-science references world-nodes for taxa (a biology chapter
   about photosynthesis references 'leaf' body-part, 'tree' plant, and
   'sunlight' phenomenon).")
